For a good solar cell, the impedance to recombination processes must be high. The charge transfer resistance at the photoanode–electrolyte interface is proportional to the lifetime of electrons (τ) at the photoanode. High charge transfer resistance and capacitance mean a longer electron lifetime and lesser probability of recombination at the electrode–electrolyte interface [48]. The recombination of electrons from the TiO2 conduction band to the redox electrolyte reduces the efficiency of the cell. Hence, a higher value of τ is favorable. Electron lifetimes of the three solar cell configurations were calculated using Eq. (2) [49] and are listed in Table 1:2τ=(Q∗R)1/∝.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
